---
---

<section class="py-32 px-6 bg-gradient-to-b from-transparent via-red-950/20 to-transparent border-y border-red-900/30">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto space-y-16">
    <!-- Section header -->
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1 bg-red-500/10 border border-red-500/40 rounded-full text-sm text-red-400 font-medium">
        <span>⚠</span>
        <span>THE PROBLEM</span>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-6xl font-black leading-tight">
          Your agent prompts are<br />
          <span class="bg-gradient-to-r from-red-400 to-orange-400 bg-clip-text text-transparent">
            held together by duct tape
          </span>
        </h2>

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          When your team works on a single large <code class="bg-gray-800 px-2 py-1 rounded text-red-300 font-medium">CLAUDE.md</code> or <code class="bg-gray-800 px-2 py-1 rounded text-red-300 font-medium">AGENTS.md</code> file, merge conflicts are inevitable. But these aren't simple git conflicts—they're <strong>semantic conflicts in instruction logic</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Two-column: pain points + visual conflict -->
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
      <!-- Left: The real costs -->
      <div class="space-y-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-red-400 uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">The Reality</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Your team wants to work in parallel. Alice is updating the role. Bob is adding tools. Carol is improving system context. But the moment someone pushes, you have a merge conflict that requires manual resolution.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Pain point cards -->
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 bg-red-950/40 px-6 py-4 rounded-r">
            <div class="text-sm font-bold text-red-400 mb-1">🐢 Velocity hit</div>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Resolving conflicts requires understanding instruction logic. That's not a syntax error—it's a code review.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 bg-orange-950/40 px-6 py-4 rounded-r">
            <div class="text-sm font-bold text-orange-400 mb-1">⚠️ Human error</div>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Merge the wrong version? Deploy instructions that conflict? Spend hours debugging which version was correct?
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 bg-red-950/40 px-6 py-4 rounded-r">
            <div class="text-sm font-bold text-red-400 mb-1">🔗 Broken traceability</div>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Git blame becomes meaningless. Code reviews are hard to follow. You can't tell why an instruction was changed.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Right: Conflict visualization -->
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="text-xs font-bold text-red-400 uppercase tracking-wide">Typical merge scenario</div>

        <div class="bg-red-950/40 border border-red-900/50 rounded-xl p-6 overflow-x-auto font-mono text-sm">
          <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
            <!-- Left side (HEAD) -->
            <div class="bg-gray-950/60 border-l-4 border-red-500 px-3 py-2">
              <div class="text-red-400 font-bold text-xs mb-1">← ALICE'S CHANGES (HEAD)</div>
              <pre class="text-xs"><code><span class="text-gray-400">You are a</span> <span class="text-red-300">senior architect</span>
<span class="text-gray-400">focused on</span> <span class="text-red-300">systems design</span>
<span class="text-gray-400">with expertise in</span>
<span class="text-red-300">scalability</span></code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Conflict indicator -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-yellow-500 font-bold text-xs">
              <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-yellow-600/50"></div>
              ⚔️ CONFLICT
              <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-yellow-600/50"></div>
            </div>

            <!-- Right side (incoming) -->
            <div class="bg-gray-950/60 border-l-4 border-yellow-600 px-3 py-2">
              <div class="text-yellow-500 font-bold text-xs mb-1">BOB'S CHANGES →</div>
              <pre class="text-xs"><code><span class="text-gray-400">You are a</span> <span class="text-yellow-300">Python code reviewer</span>
<span class="text-gray-400">who catches</span> <span class="text-yellow-300">bugs</span>
<span class="text-gray-400">and</span> <span class="text-yellow-300">performance issues</span></code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Question -->
            <div class="text-center text-gray-400 text-xs pt-2">
              <span class="bg-gray-900 px-3 py-1 rounded inline-block">
                Which one is correct? Both? Neither?
              </span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">
          This happens <strong>every time</strong> two developers edit the same agent file. And the cost isn't just the time to resolve—it's the risk of choosing wrong.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Bottom callout: scale pain -->
    <div class="border border-red-900/50 bg-red-950/20 rounded-xl p-8">
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        <span class="text-red-400 font-bold">The core issue:</span> Merge conflicts in Markdown aren't syntax errors. They're semantic conflicts. Resolving them requires understanding instruction intent, not just applying merge strategy. At scale, this becomes a bottleneck for any team managing multiple agents.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
